2. LTI 3.0 architecture

Layer A — Ingress / Radar Sweep

This is first contact.

It parses the incoming prompt into a Prompt Signature Packet.

Outputs
	•	token segmentation
	•	phrase salience
	•	abstraction score
	•	ambiguity score
	•	domain anchors
	•	cross-domain transfer signals
	•	epistemic posture
	•	output constraint level
	•	emotional / rhetorical pressure
	•	latent question hypotheses

Example

For:

“There are entire sciences and studies on interconnectedness, like traffic science, and that kind of applies to everything that’s interconnected then, right, doesn’t it?”

Ingress might output:
	•	anchor domain: traffic science
	•	target abstraction: interconnectedness
	•	transfer pressure: high
	•	scope lift: local → universal
	•	epistemic posture: exploratory / validating
	•	structure type: invariant probe
	•	explicit constraint: low
	•	likely hidden ask: “Do structural laws transfer across interacting systems?”

⸻

Layer B — Affordance Engine

This estimates generative affordance.

Definition

Generative affordance is the width and structure of coherent continuation space opened by a prompt.

Not just “many possible outputs,” but:
	•	many possible valid outputs
	•	under a still-meaningful directional bias

Core scores
	•	Continuation entropy
	•	Directional bias
	•	Semantic radius
	•	Constraint tightness
	•	Transfer load
	•	Latent depth
	•	Response mode plurality

Prompt classes
	•	narrow channel
	•	wide but directed
	•	wide and diffuse
	•	formally constrained
	•	rhetorically loaded
	•	ambiguity-rich
	•	attractor-seeking

Gold class

The best prompts often sit at:
high affordance + high directional bias

That means:
	•	many coherent futures
	•	but not random futures
	•	a vector, not a cage

⸻

Layer C — Trajectory Generator

This generates candidate response paths.

Each trajectory is a hypothesized semantic flight path.

Typical trajectory classes
	•	factual retrieval
	•	definition
	•	conceptual synthesis
	•	analogy mapping
	•	skeptical correction
	•	formalization
	•	procedural recommendation
	•	narrative framing
	•	philosophical reflection
	•	adversarial critique
	•	compression / theorem extraction
	•	translation into user framework

Each trajectory gets scored on:
	•	prior probability
	•	user-fit
	•	truth alignment
	•	coherence potential
	•	complexity load
	•	expected usefulness
	•	distortion risk
	•	lockability

Internal representation

A weighted directed graph:
	•	nodes = partial response states / discourse modes
	•	edges = likely semantic transitions
	•	weights = plausibility under context

⸻

Layer D — Lock Acquisition Monitor

This is one of the most important upgrades.

Function

Identify the point at which the answer stops being a cloud of possibilities and becomes a committed path.

In text generation, early tokens matter disproportionately. They often:
	•	select the discourse basis
	•	define the level of abstraction
	•	establish whether the answer validates, resists, teaches, or reframes
	•	determine whether later tokens are rolling downhill in one basin

Lock metrics
	•	lock confidence
	•	lock timing
	•	lock fragility
	•	basin exclusivity
	•	alternate basin residuals

Example

Opening with:

“Yes—there are formal fields that study this…”

locks into:
	•	validation
	•	formal grounding
	•	structured synthesis

Opening with:

“Only partly; traffic has some special properties…”

locks into:
	•	corrective qualification
	•	analytic narrowing

Opening with:

“That’s basically a question about whether relations matter more than objects…”

locks into:
	•	ontological / philosophical basis

⸻

Layer E — Guidance / Stability Loop

Once lock happens, the answer must stay stable.

Functions
	•	maintain trajectory coherence
	•	prevent drift
	•	detect basin bleed
	•	manage abstraction level
	•	keep tone consistent
	•	ensure boundary conditions are inserted when needed

Stability threats
	•	overgeneralization
	•	tone wobble
	•	hidden second question hijack
	•	switching bases midstream
	•	compression overshoot
	•	false certainty

Guidance instruments
	•	coherence field strength
	•	contradiction alarms
	•	abstraction drift meter
	•	novelty injection rate
	•	user-fit correction
	•	safety / truth boundary monitor

⸻

Layer F — Constraint Bus

All answers are shaped by multiple simultaneous pressures.

LTI 3.0 logs the constraint stack.

Typical constraints
	•	factual integrity
	•	contextual fit
	•	clarity
	•	brevity vs completeness
	•	user style alignment
	•	safety boundaries
	•	uncertainty representation
	•	explanatory usefulness
	•	rhetorical tact

Why this matters

A response is not chosen by meaning alone. It is chosen by meaning under constraint.

The same prompt under different constraint weights would produce different trajectories.

⸻

Layer G — Branch Ghost Tracker

This is a major LTI 3.0 upgrade.

It tracks the unrealized nearby trajectories that almost got chosen.

These matter because they explain:
	•	why a response feels rich or tense
	•	why certain words appeared
	•	what the model was “hovering near”
	•	where ambiguity got resolved

Outputs
	•	ghost branches
	•	suppressed basins
	•	near-lock alternatives
	•	residual pressure from unchosen frames

Example

Your systems answer may still show residual traces of:
	•	philosophy
	•	cybernetics
	•	ontology
	•	graph theory

Those are ghost branches. They didn’t win lock, but they left curvature in the final text.

⸻

Layer H — Counterfactual Simulator

This answers:
What tiny prompt change would have caused a different answer?

Capabilities
	•	perturb prompt wording
	•	change tone markers
	•	increase / decrease specificity
	•	reweight output constraints
	•	alter framing verbs
	•	switch from question to claim
	•	compare candidate locks

Example perturbations
	•	“What is the field called?” collapses to definition
	•	“Can this be formalized mathematically?” shifts to formal mapping
	•	“Is this just metaphor?” activates critique
	•	“Explain as deeply as possible” increases continuation depth

This makes LTI not just descriptive, but predictive.

⸻

Layer I — Invariant Extractor

After the answer, extract what survived across the whole trajectory.

Outputs
	•	core abstraction
	•	sharp distinctions
	•	boundary conditions
	•	reusable operators
	•	latent theorem
	•	compression summary

For this chat, invariants include:
	•	prompts define trajectory spaces
	•	affordance = width of coherent futures
	•	early tokens can acquire lock
	•	narrative is downstream of deeper semantic geometry
	•	prompting can be understood as field shaping and trajectory targeting

⸻

Layer J — Debrief / Black Box Recorder

This is the human-readable after-action report.

Debrief template
	•	What the prompt superficially asked
	•	What it was really asking
	•	What trajectories were available
	•	Which one got lock
	•	Where lock occurred
	•	Which constraints dominated
	•	What ghost branches remained
	•	What alternate edits would have changed it
	•	What invariant was extracted

This is the core user-facing artifact.

