3. New upgrades in LTI 3.0

Upgrade 1 — Multi-Basis Interpreter

One prompt can be answered in different bases:
	•	narrative
	•	analytic
	•	mathematical
	•	procedural
	•	poetic
	•	strategic
	•	ontological
	•	systems

LTI 3.0 explicitly models basis selection.

This matters because many disagreements are not content disagreements; they are basis mismatches.

⸻

Upgrade 2 — Semantic Phase-State Tracker

Prompts and responses can be tracked as states:
	•	diffuse
	•	exploratory
	•	convergent
	•	locked
	•	overcompressed
	•	unstable
	•	bifurcating

This lets the black box detect:
	•	premature lock
	•	healthy exploration
	•	unstable convergence
	•	phase transition from exploration to theorem

⸻

Upgrade 3 — Entropy Decay Monitor

Tracks how fast the continuation space collapses.

Too fast:
	•	brittle / literal answers
	•	missed nuance

Too slow:
	•	rambling
	•	indecision
	•	basin wobble

Ideal:
	•	enough exploration to find the right basin
	•	enough compression to deliver clarity

⸻

Upgrade 4 — Trajectory Quality Scoring

Not all coherent answers are equally good.

Quality score components:
	•	truthfulness
	•	usefulness
	•	basin fit
	•	elegance
	•	minimal distortion
	•	user resonance
	•	invariance preservation
	•	reversible interpretation

