4. Formal concepts in LTI 3.0

Prompt as field generator

A prompt induces a field over semantic space.

This field has:
	•	peaks
	•	wells
	•	ridges
	•	corridors
	•	forbidden zones
	•	low-energy routes

A response is a path through that field.

⸻

Trajectory

A trajectory is a temporally ordered semantic path chosen under:
	•	probability
	•	coherence
	•	constraint satisfaction
	•	user-fit
	•	truth alignment

⸻

Attractor basin

A region of response space where once entered, subsequent generation tends to stay within a stable mode.

Examples:
	•	explanatory synthesis
	•	adversarial critique
	•	instructional guide
	•	theorem extraction

⸻

Lock event

The point at which the system commits to one basin strongly enough that alternate futures rapidly lose probability mass.

⸻

Ghost branch

A near-selected alternate trajectory whose influence remains visible as tension, vocabulary, or structure in the final answer.

⸻

Affordance

The number and structure of coherent continuation paths.

Not raw entropy alone.
Better:
affordance = entropy shaped by meaningful directional constraints

⸻

Distortion

The information lost or deformed when one basis or basin is chosen over others.

