10. What makes prompts high-affordance, formally

This deserves its own submodule.

High-affordance prompt features
	•	abstract nouns with wide semantic radius
	•	cross-domain bridge language
	•	low imposed output format
	•	soft epistemic posture
	•	hidden structure richer than literal wording
	•	incomplete but directional questions
	•	ambiguous terms with productive curvature
	•	unresolved basis selection
	•	strong implied transfer demand
	•	underdetermined correctness criteria

Low-affordance prompt features
	•	narrow factual target
	•	strict output formatting
	•	single-domain specificity
	•	explicit correctness conditions
	•	low ambiguity
	•	low abstraction
	•	short continuation horizon

Best-performing class

Not merely high affordance.
Best is:
wide continuation space + meaningful vector bias + recoverable lock

